# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: box-violin-plots
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:box-violin-plots/bagplot] A **bagplot**, or **starburst plot**, is a method in robust statistics for visualizing two- or three-dimensional statistical data, analogous to the one-dimensional box plot.
[src:box-violin-plots/bagplot] Introduced in 1999 by Rousseuw et al., the bagplot allows one to visualize the location, spread, skewness, and outliers of a data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/bagplot] The bagplot consists of three nested polygons, called the "bag", the "fence", and the "loop".
[src:box-violin-plots/bagplot] An asterisk symbol (*) near the center of the graph is used to mark the depth median, the point with the highest possible Tukey depth.
[src:box-violin-plots/bagplot] The observations between the bag and fence are marked by line segments, on a line to the depth median, connecting them to the bag.
[src:box-violin-plots/bagplot] The three-dimensional version consists of an inner and outer bag.
[src:box-violin-plots/bagplot] The outer bag must be drawn in transparent colors so that the inner bag remains visible.
[src:box-violin-plots/bagplot] The bagplot is invariant under affine transformations of the plane, and robust against outliers.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] In descriptive statistics, a **box plot** or **boxplot** is a method for demonstrating graphically the locality, spread and skewness groups of numerical data through their quartiles.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] In addition to the box on a box plot, there can be lines (which are called *whiskers*) extending from the box indicating variability outside the upper and lower quartiles, thus, the plot is also called the **box-and-whisker plot** and the **box-and-whisker diagram**.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Outliers that differ significantly from the rest of the dataset may be plotted as individual points beyond the whiskers on the box plot.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Box plots are non-parametric: they display variation in samples of a statistical population without making any assumptions of the underlying statistical distribution (though Tukey's box plot assumes symmetry for the whiskers and normality for their length).
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The spacings in each subsection of the box plot indicate the degree of dispersion (spread) and skewness of the data, which are usually described using the five-number summary.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] In addition, the box plot allows one to visually estimate various L-estimators, notably the interquartile range, midhinge, range, mid-range, and trimean.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Box plots can be drawn either horizontally or vertically.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The range-bar method was first introduced by Mary Eleanor Spear in her book "Charting Statistics" in 1952 and again in her book "Practical Charting Techniques" in 1969.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The box-and-whisker plot was first introduced in 1970 by John Tukey, who later published on the subject in his book "Exploratory Data Analysis" in 1977.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] A box plot is a standardized way of displaying the dataset based on the five-number summary: the minimum, the maximum, the sample median, and the first and third quartiles.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The box is drawn from *Q*1 to *Q*3 with a horizontal line drawn inside it to denote the median.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Some box plots include an additional character to represent the mean of the data.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The whiskers must end at an observed data point, but can be defined in various ways.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] In the most straightforward method, the boundary of the lower whisker is the minimum value of the data set, and the boundary of the upper whisker is the maximum value of the data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Because of this variability, it is appropriate to describe the convention that is being used for the whiskers and outliers in the caption of the box plot.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Another popular choice for the boundaries of the whiskers is based on the 1.5 IQR value.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] From above the upper quartile (***Q*3**), a distance of 1.5 times the IQR is measured out and a whisker is drawn *up to* the largest observed data point from the dataset that falls within this distance.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Similarly, a distance of 1.5 times the IQR is measured out below the lower quartile (***Q*1**) and a whisker is drawn *down to* the lowest observed data point from the dataset that falls within this distance.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Because the whiskers must end at an observed data point, the whisker lengths can look unequal, even though 1.5 IQR is the same for both sides.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] All other observed data points outside the boundary of the whiskers are plotted as **outliers**.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The outliers can be plotted on the box plot as a dot, a small circle, a star, *etc.* (see example below).
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Rarely, box plot can be plotted without the whiskers.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] This can be appropriate for sensitive information to avoid whiskers (and outliers) disclosing actual values observed.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The unusual percentiles 2%, 9%, 91%, 98% are sometimes used for whisker cross-hatches and whisker ends to depict the seven-number summary.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] If the data are normally distributed, the locations of the seven marks on the box plot will be equally spaced.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] On some box plots, a cross-hatch is placed before the end of each whisker.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Tukey first popularized this type of visual data display in 1969, several variations on the classical box plot have been developed, and the two most commonly found variations are the variable-width box plots and the notched box plots.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] One convention for obtaining the boundaries of these notches is to use a distance of $\pm {\frac {1.58{\text{ IQR}}}{\sqrt {n}}}$ around the median.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] For a symmetrical data distribution, the medcouple will be zero, and this reduces the adjusted box plot to the Tukey's box plot with equal whisker lengths of $1.5{\text{ IQR}}$ for both whiskers.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] A series of hourly temperatures were measured throughout the day in degrees Fahrenheit.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] A box plot of the data set can be generated by first calculating five relevant values of this data set: minimum, maximum, median (***Q*2**), first quartile (***Q*1**), and third quartile (***Q*3**).
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The minimum is the smallest number of the data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] In this case, the minimum recorded day temperature is 57°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The maximum is the largest number of the data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] In this case, the maximum recorded day temperature is 81°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The median is the "middle" number of the ordered data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] This means that exactly 50% of the elements are below the median and 50% of the elements are greater than the median.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The median of this ordered data set is 70°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The first quartile value (***Q*1** **or 25th percentile)** is the number that marks one quarter of the ordered data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] In other words, there are exactly 25% of the elements that are less than the first quartile and exactly 75% of the elements that are greater than it.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The first quartile value can be easily determined by finding the "middle" number between the minimum and the median.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] For the hourly temperatures, the "middle" number found between 57°F and 70°F is 66°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The third quartile value (***Q*3** **or 75th percentile)** is the number that marks three quarters of the ordered data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] In other words, there are exactly 75% of the elements that are less than the third quartile and 25% of the elements that are greater than it.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The third quartile value can be easily obtained by finding the "middle" number between the median and the maximum.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] For the hourly temperatures, the "middle" number between 70°F and 81°F is 75°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The upper whisker boundary of the box plot is the largest data value that is within 1.5 IQR above the third quartile.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Here, 1.5 IQR above the third quartile is 88.5°F and the maximum is 81°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Therefore, the upper whisker is drawn at the value of the maximum, which is 81°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Similarly, the lower whisker boundary of the box plot is the smallest data value that is within 1.5 IQR below the first quartile.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Here, 1.5 IQR below the first quartile is 52.5°F and the minimum is 57°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Therefore, the lower whisker is drawn at the value of the minimum, which is 57°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] In this example, only the first and the last number are changed.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The median, third quartile, and first quartile remain the same.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] In this case, the maximum value in this data set is 89°F, and 1.5 IQR above the third quartile is 88.5°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The maximum is greater than 1.5 IQR plus the third quartile, so the maximum is an outlier.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Therefore, the upper whisker is drawn at the greatest value smaller than 1.5 IQR above the third quartile, which is 79°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Similarly, the minimum value in this data set is 52°F, and 1.5 IQR below the first quartile is 52.5°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] The minimum is smaller than 1.5 IQR minus the first quartile, so the minimum is also an outlier.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Therefore, the lower whisker is drawn at the smallest value greater than 1.5 IQR below the first quartile, which is 57°F.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Using the above example that has 24 data points (*n* = 24), one can calculate the median, first and third quartile either mathematically or visually.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Although box plots may seem more primitive than histograms or kernel density estimates, they do have a number of advantages.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] First, the box plot enables statisticians to do a quick graphical examination on one or more data sets.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Box plots also take up less space and are therefore particularly useful for comparing distributions between several groups or sets of data in parallel.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Lastly, the overall structure of histograms and kernel density estimate can be strongly influenced by the choice of number and width of bins techniques and the choice of bandwidth, respectively.
[src:box-violin-plots/box-plot] Although looking at a statistical distribution is more common than looking at a box plot, it can be useful to compare the box plot against the probability density function (theoretical histogram) for a normal N(0,*σ*2) distribution and observe their characteristics directly.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis refers to a family of algorithms and tasks rather than one specific algorithm.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] It can be achieved by various algorithms that differ significantly in their understanding of what constitutes a cluster and how to efficiently find them.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Popular notions of clusters include groups with small distances between cluster members, dense areas of the data space, intervals or particular statistical distributions.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Clustering can therefore be formulated as a multi-objective optimization problem.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The appropriate clustering algorithm and parameter settings (including parameters such as the distance function to use, a density threshold or the number of expected clusters) depend on the individual data set and intended use of the results.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis as such is not an automatic task, but an iterative process of knowledge discovery or interactive multi-objective optimization that involves trial and failure.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] It is often necessary to modify data preprocessing and model parameters until the result achieves the desired properties.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Besides the term *clustering*, there are a number of terms with similar meanings, including *automatic classification*, *numerical taxonomy*, *botryology* (from Greek: βότρυς 'grape'), *typological analysis*, and *community detection*.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The subtle differences are often in the use of the results: while in data mining, the resulting groups are the matter of interest, in automatic classification the resulting discriminative power is of interest.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Cluster analysis originated in anthropology by Driver and Kroeber in 1932 and introduced to psychology by Joseph Zubin in 1938 and Robert Tryon in 1939 and famously used by Cattell beginning in 1943 for trait theory classification in personality psychology.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The notion of a "cluster" cannot be precisely defined, which is one of the reasons why there are so many clustering algorithms.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] There is a common denominator: a group of data objects.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] However, different researchers employ different cluster models, and for each of these cluster models again different algorithms can be given.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The notion of a cluster, as found by different algorithms, varies significantly in its properties.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Understanding these "cluster models" is key to understanding the differences between the various algorithms.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] A "clustering" is essentially a set of such clusters, usually containing all objects in the data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, it may specify the relationship of the clusters to each other, for example, a hierarchy of clusters embedded in each other.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] As listed above, clustering algorithms can be categorized based on their cluster model.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The following overview will only list the most prominent examples of clustering algorithms, as there are possibly over 100 published clustering algorithms.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Not all provide models for their clusters and can thus not easily be categorized.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] An overview of algorithms explained in Wikipedia can be found in the list of statistics algorithms.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The most appropriate clustering algorithm for a particular problem often needs to be chosen experimentally, unless there is a mathematical reason to prefer one cluster model over another.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] An algorithm that is designed for one kind of model will generally fail on a data set that contains a radically different kind of model.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means cannot find non-convex clusters.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Most traditional clustering methods assume the clusters exhibit a spherical, elliptical or convex shape.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Connectivity-based clustering, also known as hierarchical clustering, is based on the idea that objects are more related to nearby objects than to those farther away.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] These algorithms form clusters by connecting objects based on their distance.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] A cluster can be understood in terms of the maximum distance required to connect its elements.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] At different distance thresholds, different cluster groupings appear.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] These groupings can be visualized using a dendrogram, a tree-like diagram that shows how clusters merge as the distance increases.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This explains the term "hierarchical clustering": instead of producing a single partition of the data set, the algorithm builds a hierarchy of clusters that merge at different distances.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In a dendrogram, the y-axis shows the distance at which clusters merge, while the x-axis arranges objects so that clusters appear as continuous branches.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Connectivity-based clustering is a family of methods that differ in how distances between clusters are computed.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In addition to choosing a distance function, the user must also select a **linkage criterion**, which determines how the distance between clusters is calculated.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Common linkage criteria include single-linkage clustering (minimum distance between points), complete linkage clustering (maximum distance), and UPGMA or WPGMA (average linkage based on mean distances).
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Hierarchical clustering can be either agglomerative (starting with individual elements and merging them) or divisive (starting with the full data set and splitting it).
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Identify the two closest clusters based on a chosen distance measure.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Recalculate distances between the new cluster and the remaining clusters using the selected linkage criterion.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Repeat until all data points are merged into a single cluster.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This process produces a full hierarchy of possible clusterings rather than a single final result.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] A specific clustering can be obtained by selecting a cut level in the dendrogram, which determines how many clusters are formed.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] These methods do not produce a unique partitioning of the data set, but rather a hierarchy from which the user must choose appropriate clusters.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] They are also sensitive to outliers, which may appear as separate clusters or cause other clusters to merge.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This effect, especially in single-linkage clustering, is known as the "chaining phenomenon".
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In the general case, the complexity is ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{3})$ for agglomerative clustering and ${\mathcal {O}}(2^{n-1})$ for divisive clustering, which makes them computationally expensive for large data sets.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] For some special cases, more efficient methods (with complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2})$ ) are known, such as SLINK for single-linkage and CLINK for complete-linkage clustering.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In centroid-based clustering, each cluster is represented by a central vector, which is not necessarily a member of the data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] When the number of clusters is fixed to *k*, *k*-means clustering gives a formal definition as an optimization problem: find the *k* cluster centers and assign the objects to the nearest cluster center, such that the squared distances from the cluster are minimized.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The optimization problem itself is known to be NP-hard, and thus the common approach is to search only for approximate solutions.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] A particularly well-known approximate method is Lloyd's algorithm, often just referred to as "*k-means algorithm*" (although another algorithm introduced this name).
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] It does however only find a local optimum, and is commonly run multiple times with different random initializations.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Most *k*-means-type algorithms require the number of clusters – *k* – to be specified in advance, which is considered to be one of the biggest drawbacks of these algorithms.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Furthermore, the algorithms prefer clusters of approximately similar size, as they will always assign an object to the nearest centroid; often yielding improperly cut borders of clusters.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This happens primarily because the algorithm optimizes cluster centers, not cluster borders.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Assign each observation to the centroid to which it has the smallest squared Euclidean distance.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This results in *k* distinct groups, each containing unique observations.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Recalculate centroids (see *k*-means clustering).
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Exit *iff* the new centroids are equivalent to the previous iteration's centroids.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Else, repeat the algorithm, the centroids have yet to converge.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] K-means has a number of interesting theoretical properties.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] First, it partitions the data space into a structure known as a Voronoi diagram.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Second, it is conceptually close to nearest neighbor classification, and as such is popular in machine learning.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Third, it can be seen as a variation of model-based clustering, and Lloyd's algorithm as a variation of the Expectation-maximization algorithm for this model discussed below.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The following pseudocode describes the standard iterative refinement form of *k*-means.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The algorithm alternates between an **assignment step**, which labels each point by its nearest centroid, and an **update step**, which recomputes each centroid as the mean of its assigned points.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Convergence is guaranteed in a finite number of iterations, though the result may be a local optimum.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Centroid-based clustering problems such as *k*-means and *k*-medoids are special cases of the uncapacitated, metric facility location problem, a canonical problem in the operations research and computational geometry communities.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In a basic facility location problem (of which there are numerous variants that model more elaborate settings), the task is to find the best warehouse locations to optimally service a given set of consumers.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] One may view "warehouses" as cluster centroids and "consumer locations" as the data to be clustered.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This makes it possible to apply the well-developed algorithmic solutions from the facility location literature to the presently considered centroid-based clustering problem.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The clustering framework most closely related to statistics is model-based clustering, which is based on distribution models.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This approach models the data as arising from a mixture of probability distributions.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] It has the advantages of providing principled statistical answers to questions such as how many clusters there are, what clustering method or model to use, and how to detect and deal with outliers.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] While the theoretical foundation of these methods is excellent, they suffer from overfitting unless constraints are put on the model complexity.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] A more complex model will usually be able to explain the data better, which makes choosing the appropriate model complexity inherently difficult.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Standard model-based clustering methods include more parsimonious models based on the eigenvalue decomposition of the covariance matrices, that provide a balance between overfitting and fidelity to the data.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] One prominent method is known as Gaussian mixture models (using the expectation-maximization algorithm).
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Here, the data set is usually modeled with a fixed (to avoid overfitting) number of Gaussian distributions that are initialized randomly and whose parameters are iteratively optimized to better fit the data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This will converge to a local optimum, so multiple runs may produce different results.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In order to obtain a hard clustering, objects are often then assigned to the Gaussian distribution they most likely belong to; for soft clusterings, this is not necessary.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Distribution-based clustering produces complex models for clusters that can capture correlation and dependence between attributes.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] However, these algorithms put an extra burden on the user: for many real data sets, there may be no concisely defined mathematical model (e.g. assuming Gaussian distributions is a rather strong assumption on the data).
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In density-based clustering, clusters are defined as areas of higher density than the remainder of the data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Objects in sparse areas – that are required to separate clusters – are usually considered to be noise and border points.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The most popular density-based clustering method is DBSCAN.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In contrast to many newer methods, it features a well-defined cluster model called "density-reachability".
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Similar to linkage-based clustering, it is based on connecting points within certain distance thresholds.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] However, it only connects points that satisfy a density criterion, in the original variant defined as a minimum number of other objects within this radius.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] A cluster consists of all density-connected objects (which can form a cluster of an arbitrary shape, in contrast to many other methods) plus all objects that are within these objects' range.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] OPTICS is a generalization of DBSCAN that removes the need to choose an appropriate value for the range parameter $\varepsilon$ , and produces a hierarchical result related to that of linkage clustering.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] DeLi-Clu, Density-Link-Clustering combines ideas from single-linkage clustering and OPTICS, eliminating the $\varepsilon$ parameter entirely and offering performance improvements over OPTICS by using an R-tree index.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] HDBSCAN extends DBSCAN by converting it into a hierarchical clustering algorithm, and then using a technique to extract a flat clustering based in the stability of clusters.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The key drawback of DBSCAN and OPTICS is that they expect some kind of density drop to detect cluster borders.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] On data sets with, for example, overlapping Gaussian distributions – a common use case in artificial data – the cluster borders produced by these algorithms will often look arbitrary, because the cluster density decreases continuously.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] On a data set consisting of mixtures of Gaussians, these algorithms are nearly always outperformed by methods such as EM clustering that are able to precisely model this kind of data.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Mean-shift is a clustering approach where each object is moved to the densest area in its vicinity, based on kernel density estimation.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Eventually, objects converge to local maxima of density.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Similar to k-means clustering, these "density attractors" can serve as representatives for the data set, but mean-shift can detect arbitrary-shaped clusters similar to DBSCAN.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Due to the expensive iterative procedure and density estimation, mean-shift is usually slower than DBSCAN or k-Means.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Besides that, the applicability of the mean-shift algorithm to multidimensional data is hindered by the unsmooth behaviour of the kernel density estimate, which results in over-fragmentation of cluster tails.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The grid-based technique is used for a multi-dimensional data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In this technique, we create a grid structure, and the comparison is performed on grids (also known as cells).
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The grid-based technique is fast and has low computational complexity.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] There are two types of grid-based clustering methods: STING and CLIQUE.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Randomly select a cell ‘c’, where c should not be traversed beforehand.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Calculate the density of all the neighbors of ‘c’.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] If the density of a neighboring cell is greater than threshold density then, add the cell in the cluster and repeat steps 4.2 and 4.3 till there is no neighbor with a density greater than threshold density.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Repeat steps 2, 3, and 4 till all the cells are traversed.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] With the increasing need to process Big data, the willingness to trade semantic meaning of the generated clusters for performance becomes more relevant.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Therefore, efforts have been put into improving the performance of existing algorithms.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This led to the development of pre-clustering methods such as canopy clustering, which can process huge data sets efficiently, but the resulting "clusters" are merely a rough pre-partitioning of the data set to then analyze the partitions with existing slower methods such as k-means clustering.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] For high-dimensional data, many methods fail due to the curse of dimensionality, which renders particular distance functions problematic in high-dimensional spaces.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Examples for such clustering algorithms are CLIQUE and SUBCLU.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Several different clustering systems based on mutual information have been proposed.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] One is Marina Meilă's *variation of information* metric; another provides hierarchical clustering.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Using genetic algorithms, a wide range of different fit-functions can be optimized, including mutual information.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Also belief propagation, a recent development in computer science and statistical physics, has led to the creation of new types of clustering algorithms.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Evaluation (or "validation") of clustering results is as difficult as the clustering itself.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Internal evaluation measures suffer from the problem that they represent functions that themselves can be seen as a clustering objective.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, one could cluster the data set by the Silhouette coefficient; except that there is no known efficient algorithm for this.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] By using such an internal measure for evaluation, one rather compares the similarity of the optimization problems, and not necessarily how useful the clustering is.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] External evaluation has similar problems: if we have such "ground truth" labels, then we would not need to cluster; and in practical applications we usually do not have such labels.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] On the other hand, the labels only reflect one possible partitioning of the data set, which does not imply that there does not exist a different, and maybe even better, clustering.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Neither of these approaches can therefore ultimately judge the actual quality of a clustering, but this needs human evaluation, which is highly subjective.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Nevertheless, such statistics can be quite informative in identifying bad clusterings, but one should not dismiss subjective human evaluation.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] When a clustering result is evaluated based on the data that was clustered itself, this is called internal evaluation.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] These methods usually assign the best score to the algorithm that produces clusters with high similarity within a cluster and low similarity between clusters.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] One drawback of using internal criteria in cluster evaluation is that high scores on an internal measure do not necessarily result in effective information retrieval applications.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, this evaluation is biased towards algorithms that use the same cluster model.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means clustering naturally optimizes object distances, and a distance-based internal criterion will likely overrate the resulting clustering.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Therefore, the internal evaluation measures are best suited to get some insight into situations where one algorithm performs better than another, but this shall not imply that one algorithm produces more valid results than another.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Validity as measured by such an index depends on the claim that this kind of structure exists in the data set.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] An algorithm designed for some kind of models has no chance if the data set contains a radically different set of models, or if the evaluation measures a radically different criterion.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, k-means clustering can only find convex clusters, and many evaluation indexes assume convex clusters.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] On a data set with non-convex clusters neither the use of *k*-means, nor of an evaluation criterion that assumes convexity, is sound.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Many internal evaluation measures are based on the intuition that items in the same cluster should be more similar than items in different clusters.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The Dunn index aims to identify dense and well-separated clusters.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] It is defined as the ratio between the minimal inter-cluster distance to maximal intra-cluster distance.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] where *d*(*i*,*j*) represents the distance between clusters *i* and *j*, and *d* '(*k*) measures the intra-cluster distance of cluster *k*.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The inter-cluster distance *d*(*i*,*j*) between two clusters may be any number of distance measures, such as the distance between the centroids of the clusters.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Similarly, the intra-cluster distance *d* '(*k*) may be measured in a variety of ways, such as the maximal distance between any pair of elements in cluster *k*.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Since internal criterion seek clusters with high intra-cluster similarity and low inter-cluster similarity, algorithms that produce clusters with high Dunn index are more desirable.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The silhouette coefficient contrasts the average distance to elements in the same cluster with the average distance to elements in other clusters.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Objects with a high silhouette value are considered well clustered, objects with a low value may be outliers.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This index works well with *k*-means clustering, and is also used to determine the optimal number of clusters.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This matrix consider pairs of objects: the distance between the pair as a scoring function and the partition pairs defined true positive, true negatives, false negatives and true negatives by considering if pairs are in the same clusters of not.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This index borrow the same characteristics as the AUC in the supervised scenario including an expected value of 0.5 and vizualisation of results.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In external evaluation, clustering results are evaluated based on data that was not used for clustering, such as known class labels and external benchmarks.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Such benchmarks consist of a set of pre-classified items, and these sets are often created by (expert) humans.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Thus, the benchmark sets can be thought of as a gold standard for evaluation.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] These types of evaluation methods measure how close the clustering is to the predetermined benchmark classes.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] However, it has recently been discussed whether this is adequate for real data, or only on synthetic data sets with a factual ground truth, since classes can contain internal structure, the attributes present may not allow separation of clusters or the classes may contain anomalies.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Additionally, from a knowledge discovery point of view, the reproduction of known knowledge may not necessarily be the intended result.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In the special scenario of constrained clustering, where meta information (such as class labels) is used already in the clustering process, the hold-out of information for evaluation purposes is non-trivial.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] A number of measures are adapted from variants used to evaluate classification tasks.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In place of counting the number of times a class was correctly assigned to a single data point (known as true positives), such *pair counting* metrics assess whether each pair of data points that is truly in the same cluster is predicted to be in the same cluster.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Purity is a measure of the extent to which clusters contain a single class.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Its calculation can be thought of as follows: For each cluster, count the number of data points from the most common class in said cluster.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Now take the sum over all clusters and divide by the total number of data points.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This measure doesn't penalize having many clusters, and more clusters will make it easier to produce a high purity.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] A purity score of 1 is always possible by putting each data point in its own cluster.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Also, purity doesn't work well for imbalanced data, where even poorly performing clustering algorithms will give a high purity value.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] For example, if a size 1000 dataset consists of two classes, one containing 999 points and the other containing 1 point, then every possible partition will have a purity of at least 99.9%.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The Rand index computes how similar the clusters (returned by the clustering algorithm) are to the benchmark classifications.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] where $TP$ is the number of true positives, $TN$ is the number of true negatives, $FP$ is the number of false positives, and $FN$ is the number of false negatives.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The instances being counted here are the number of correct *pairwise* assignments.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] That is, $TP$ is the number of pairs of points that are clustered together in the predicted partition and in the ground truth partition, $FP$ is the number of pairs of points that are clustered together in the predicted partition but not in the ground truth partition etc.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] If the dataset is of size N, then $TP+TN+FP+FN={\binom {N}{2}}$ .
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] One issue with the Rand index is that false positives and false negatives are equally weighted.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This may be an undesirable characteristic for some clustering applications.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The F-measure addresses this concern, as does the chance-corrected adjusted Rand index.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The F-measure can be used to balance the contribution of false negatives by weighting recall through a parameter $\beta \geq 0$ .
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Let **precision** and **recall** (both external evaluation measures in themselves) be defined as follows: $P={\frac {TP}{TP+FP}}$ $R={\frac {TP}{TP+FN}}$ where P is the precision rate and R is the recall rate.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In other words, recall has no impact on the F-measure when $\beta =0$ , and increasing $\beta$ allocates an increasing amount of weight to recall in the final F-measure.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Also $TN$ is not taken into account and can vary from 0 upward without bound.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index is used to quantify the similarity between two datasets.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index takes on a value between 0 and 1.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] An index of 1 means that the two dataset are identical, and an index of 0 indicates that the datasets have no common elements.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The Jaccard index is defined by the following formula: $J(A,B)={\frac {|A\cap B|}{|A\cup B|}}={\frac {TP}{TP+FP+FN}}$ This is simply the number of unique elements common to both sets divided by the total number of unique elements in both sets.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Note that $TN$ is not taken into account.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The Dice symmetric measure doubles the weight on $TP$ while still ignoring $TN$ : $DSC={\frac {2TP}{2TP+FP+FN}}$ .
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The Fowlkes–Mallows index computes the similarity between the clusters returned by the clustering algorithm and the benchmark classifications.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The higher the value of the Fowlkes–Mallows index the more similar the clusters and the benchmark classifications are.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] It can be computed using the following formula: $FM={\sqrt {{\frac {TP}{TP+FP}}\cdot {\frac {TP}{TP+FN}}}}$ where $TP$ is the number of true positives, $FP$ is the number of false positives, and $FN$ is the number of false negatives.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The $FM$ index is the geometric mean of the precision and recall P and R , and is thus also known as the G-measure, while the F-measure is their harmonic mean.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Moreover, precision and recall are also known as Wallace's indices $B^{I}$ and $B^{II}$ .
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Chance normalized versions of recall, precision and G-measure correspond to Informedness, Markedness and Matthews Correlation and relate strongly to Kappa.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The Chi index is an external validation index that measure the clustering results by applying the chi-squared statistic.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] This index scores positively the fact that the labels are as sparse as possible across the clusters, i.e., that each cluster has as few different labels as possible.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The higher the value of the Chi Index the greater the relationship between the resulting clusters and the label used.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The mutual information is an information theoretic measure of how much information is shared between a clustering and a ground-truth classification that can detect a non-linear similarity between two clustering.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Normalized mutual information is a family of corrected-for-chance variants of this that has a reduced bias for varying cluster numbers.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] A confusion matrix can be used to quickly visualize the results of a classification (or clustering) algorithm.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] It shows how different a cluster is from the gold standard cluster.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] To measure cluster tendency is to measure to what degree clusters exist in the data to be clustered, and may be performed as an initial test, before attempting clustering.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] One way to do this is to compare the data against random data.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] On average, random data should not have clusters .
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] uniformly randomly distributed data points.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] With this definition, uniform random data should tend to have values near to 0.5, and clustered data should tend to have values nearer to 1.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] , making this statistic largely useless in application (as real data never is remotely uniform).
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] As clustering algorithms are increasingly deployed by corporations and governmental organizations to categorize populations and automate decisions with real world data, concerns regarding algorithmic bias have become more prevalent.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Because clustering is a form of unsupervised learning, it identifies patterns within existing data.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Consequently, these models can inadvertently reinforce historical inequalities already existent in the training datasets.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] In response, researchers have developed "Fair Clustering" frameworks, such as the Fairlet approach, which ensures that each cluster maintains a balanced representation of protected groups relative to the overall population.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Under the legal doctrine of disparate impact, a process is considered discriminatory if it results in disproportionately adverse outcomes for a protected class, even if the algorithm is facially neutral (i.e., it does not explicitly use attributes like race or gender).
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Unfairness often occurs through proxy variables.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] For instance, even if a dataset is stripped of race, a clustering algorithm might use ZIP codes or educational background as features.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] Because these variables are often highly related to economic status and ethnicity, the resulting clusters will effectively segregate individuals by these characteristics.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p01] The application of clustering in predictive policing has demonstrated how historical bias in data can create feedback loops.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p02] Cluster analysis is used for data analysis across a wide range of fields.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p02] In the natural sciences, techniques such as hierarchical clustering, *k*-means,dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis (PCA), and t-SNE are frequently used to make sense of the dense data.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p02] In computing and technology applications, clustering is the driving force behind machine learning's unsupervised learning, and is embedded in systems ranging from search engines to recommendation platforms.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p02] Common algorithms in this field include *k*-means, DBSCAN, mean shift, and spectral clustering, often applied after feature extraction or embedding, which are steps that map raw data, such as text, images, sensor logs, into a vector space amenable to distance based grouping.
[src:box-violin-plots/cluster-analysis-p02] In business and the social sciences, clustering is most often applied to tabular survey and transaction data, where the aim is to segment populations into consumer groups, create detailed market analysis insights, or illustrate voter preferences.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] In statistics, **ranking** is the data transformation in which numerical or ordinal values are replaced by their rank when the data are sorted.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] As another example, the ordinal data hot, cold, warm would be replaced by 3, 1, 2.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] In these examples, the ranks are assigned to values in ascending order, although descending ranks can also be used.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] Ranks are related to the indexed list of order statistics, which consists of the original dataset rearranged into ascending order.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] Some kinds of statistical tests employ calculations based on ranks.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] The distribution of values in decreasing order of rank is often of interest when values vary widely in scale; this is the rank-size distribution (or rank-frequency distribution), for example for city sizes or word frequencies.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] Some ranks can have non-integer values for tied data values.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] For example, when there is an even number of copies of the same data value, the fractional statistical rank of the tied data ends in ½.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] Percentile rank is another type of statistical ranking.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] Microsoft Excel provides two ranking functions, the Rank.EQ function which assigns competition ranks in the case of ties, and the Rank.AVG function which assigns fractional ranks to ties.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] Note that Rank.AVG preserves rank sums in the case of ties, whereas Rank.EQ does not.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] This makes the latter undesirable in many statistical applications.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] The functions have the order argument, which is by default is set to *descending*, i.e. the largest number will have a rank 1.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] This is generally uncommon for statistics where the ranking is usually in ascending order, where the smallest number has a rank 1.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] A rank correlation can be used to compare two rankings for the same set of objects.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] For example, Spearman's rank correlation coefficient is useful to measure the statistical dependence between the rankings of athletes in two tournaments.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] And the Kendall rank correlation coefficient is another approach.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] Alternatively, intersection/overlap-based approaches offer additional flexibility.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] One example is the "Rank–rank hypergeometric overlap" approach, which is designed to compare ranking of the genes that are at the "top" of two ordered lists of differentially expressed genes.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] A similar approach is taken by the "Rank Biased Overlap (RBO)", which also implements an adjustable probability, p, to customize the weight assigned at a desired depth of ranking.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] These approaches have the advantages of addressing disjoint sets, sets of different sizes, and top-weightedness (taking into account the absolute ranking position, which may be ignored in standard non-weighted rank correlation approaches).
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] Let $X_{1},..X_{n}$ be a set of random variables.
[src:box-violin-plots/ranking-statistics] If all the values are unique, the rank of variable number i is the unique solution $R_{n,i}$ to the equation $X_{i}=X_{N,(R_{n,i})}$ .
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] In statistics, **restricted randomization** occurs in the design of experiments and in particular in the context of randomized experiments and randomized controlled trials.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Restricted randomization allows intuitively poor allocations of treatments to experimental units to be avoided, while retaining the theoretical benefits of randomization.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] For example, in a clinical trial of a new proposed treatment of obesity compared to a control, an experimenter would want to avoid outcomes of the randomization in which the new treatment was allocated only to the heaviest patients.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The concept was introduced by Frank Yates (1948) and William J.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Consider a batch process that uses 7 monitor wafers in each run.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The plan further calls for measuring a response variable on each wafer at each of 9 sites.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The organization of the sampling plan has a hierarchical or nested structure: the batch run is the topmost level, the second level is an individual wafer, and the third level is the site on the wafer.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The total amount of data generated per batch run will be 7 · 9 = 63 observations.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] One approach to analyzing these data would be to compute the mean of all these points as well as their standard deviation and use those results as responses for each run.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Analyzing the data as suggested above is not absolutely incorrect, but doing so loses information that one might otherwise obtain.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] For example, site 1 on wafer 1 is physically different from site 1 on wafer 2 or on any other wafer.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The same is true for any of the sites on any of the wafers.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Similarly, wafer 1 in run 1 is physically different from wafer 1 in run 2, and so on.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] To describe this situation one says that sites are nested within wafers while wafers are nested within runs.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] As a consequence of this nesting, there are restrictions on the randomization that can occur in the experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] This kind of restricted randomization always produces nested sources of variation.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Examples of nested variation or restricted randomization discussed on this page are **split-plot** and **strip-plot designs**.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The objective of an experiment with this type of sampling plan is generally to reduce the variability due to sites on the wafers and wafers within runs (or batches) in the process.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The sites on the wafers and the wafers within a batch become sources of unwanted variation and an investigator seeks to make the system robust to those sources—in other words, one could treat wafers and sites as noise factors in such an experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Because the wafers and the sites represent unwanted sources of variation and because one of the objectives is to reduce the process sensitivity to these sources of variation, treating wafers and sites as random effects in the analysis of the data is a reasonable approach.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] In other words, nested variation is often another way of saying nested random effects or nested sources of noise.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] If the factors "wafers" and "sites" are treated as random effects, then it is possible to estimate a variance component due to each source of variation through analysis of variance techniques.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Once estimates of the variance components have been obtained, an investigator is then able to determine the largest source of variation in the process under experimentation, and also determine the magnitudes of the other sources of variation in relation to the largest source.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] If an experiment or process has nested variation, the experiment or process has multiple sources of random error that affect its output.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Having nested random effects in a model is the same thing as having nested variation in a model.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Split-plot designs result when a particular type of restricted randomization has occurred during the experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] A simple factorial experiment can result in a split-plot type of design because of the way the experiment was actually executed.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] 3. experimental units are processed individually, one right after the other, for the same treatment combination without resetting the factor settings for that treatment combination.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] An experiment run under one of the above three situations usually results in a split-plot type of design.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Consider an experiment to examine electroplating of aluminum (non-aqueous) on copper strips.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The three factors of interest are: current (A); solution temperature (T); and the solution concentration of the plating agent (S).
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] There are a total of 16 copper strips available for the experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Consider running the experiment under the first condition listed above, with the factor solution concentration of the plating agent (S) being hard to vary.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Since this factor is hard to vary, the experimenter would like to randomize the treatment combinations so that the solution concentration factor has a minimal number of changes.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] In other words, the randomization of the treatment runs is restricted somewhat by the level of the solution concentration factor.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] As a result, the treatment combinations might be randomized such that those treatment runs corresponding to one level of the concentration (−1) are run first.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Each copper strip is individually plated, meaning only one strip at a time is placed in the solution for a given treatment combination.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Once the four runs at the low level of solution concentration have been completed, the solution is changed to the high level of concentration (1), and the remaining four runs of the experiment are performed (where again, each strip is individually plated).
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Once one complete replicate of the experiment has been completed, a second replicate is performed with a set of four copper strips processed for a given level of solution concentration before changing the concentration and processing the remaining four strips.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Note that the levels for the remaining two factors can still be randomized.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] In addition, the level of concentration that is run first in the replication runs can also be randomized.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Running the experiment in this way results in a **split-plot design**.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Solution concentration is known as the **whole plot** factor and the **subplot factors** are the current and the solution temperature.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] A split-plot design has more than one size experimental unit.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] In this experiment, one size experimental unit is an individual copper strip.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The treatments or factors that were applied to the individual strips are solution temperature and current (these factors were changed each time a new strip was placed in the solution).
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The other or larger size experimental unit is a set of four copper strips.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The treatment or factor that was applied to a set of four strips is solution concentration (this factor was changed after four strips were processed).
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The smaller size experimental unit is referred to as the **subplot experimental unit**, while the larger experimental unit is referred to as the **whole plot unit**.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] There are 16 subplot experimental units for this experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Solution temperature and current are the subplot factors in this experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] There are four whole-plot experimental units in this experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Solution concentration is the whole-plot factor in this experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Since there are two sizes of experimental units, there are two error terms in the model, one that corresponds to the whole-plot error or whole-plot experimental unit and one that corresponds to the subplot error or subplot experimental unit.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The first three sources are from the whole-plot level, while the next 12 are from the subplot portion.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] A normal probability plot of the 12 subplot term estimates could be used to look for statistically significant terms.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Consider running the experiment under the second condition listed above (i.e., a batch process) for which four copper strips are placed in the solution at one time.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] A specified level of current can be applied to an individual strip within the solution.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The same 16 treatment combinations (a replicated 23 factorial) are run as were run under the first scenario.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] However, the way in which the experiment is performed would be different.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] There are four treatment combinations of solution temperature and solution concentration: (−1, −1), (−1, 1), (1, −1), (1, 1).
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The experimenter randomly chooses one of these four treatments to set up first.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Four copper strips are placed in the solution.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Two of the four strips are randomly assigned to the low current level.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The remaining two strips are assigned to the high current level.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The plating is performed and the response is measured.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] A second treatment combination of temperature and concentration is chosen and the same procedure is followed.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] This is done for all four temperature / concentration combinations.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Running the experiment in this way also results in a split-plot design in which the whole-plot factors are now solution concentration and solution temperature, and the subplot factor is current.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] In this experiment, one size experimental unit is again an individual copper strip.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The treatment or factor that was applied to the individual strips is current (this factor was changed each time for a different strip within the solution).
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The other or larger size experimental unit is again a set of four copper strips.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The treatments or factors that were applied to a set of four strips are solution concentration and solution temperature (these factors were changed after four strips were processed).
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The smaller size experimental unit is again referred to as the subplot experimental unit.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Current is the subplot factor in this experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The larger-size experimental unit is the whole-plot experimental unit.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] There are four whole plot experimental units in this experiment and solution concentration and solution temperature are the whole plot factors in this experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] There are two sizes of experimental units and there are two error terms in the model: one that corresponds to the whole-plot error or whole-plot experimental unit, and one that corresponds to the subplot error or subplot experimental unit.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The first three sources come from the whole-plot level and the next 5 come from the subplot level.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Since there are 8 degrees of freedom for the subplot error term, this MSE can be used to test each effect that involves current.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Consider running the experiment under the third scenario listed above.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] There is only one copper strip in the solution at one time.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] However, two strips, one at the low current and one at the high current, are processed one right after the other under the same temperature and concentration setting.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Once two strips have been processed, the concentration is changed and the temperature is reset to another combination.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Two strips are again processed, one after the other, under this temperature and concentration setting.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] This process is continued until all 16 copper strips have been processed.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Running the experiment in this way also results in a split-plot design in which the whole-plot factors are again solution concentration and solution temperature and the subplot factor is current.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The other or larger-size experimental unit is a set of two copper strips.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The treatments or factors that were applied to a pair of two strips are solution concentration and solution temperature (these factors were changed after two strips were processed).
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The smaller size experimental unit is referred to as the subplot experimental unit.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Current is the subplot factor in the experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] There are eight whole-plot experimental units in this experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Solution concentration and solution temperature are the whole plot factors.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] There are two error terms in the model, one that corresponds to the whole-plot error or whole-plot experimental unit, and one that corresponds to the subplot error or subplot experimental unit.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The first four terms come from the whole-plot analysis and the next 5 terms come from the subplot analysis.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Note that we have separate error terms for both the whole plot and the subplot effects, each based on 4 degrees of freedom.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] As can be seen from these three scenarios, one of the major differences in split-plot designs versus simple factorial designs is the number of different sizes of experimental units in the experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Split-plot designs have more than one size experimental unit, i.e., more than one error term.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Since these designs involve different sizes of experimental units and different variances, the standard errors of the various mean comparisons involve one or more of the variances.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Specifying the appropriate model for a split-plot design involves being able to identify each size of experimental unit.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] As a result of having greater than one size experimental unit, the appropriate model used to analyze split-plot designs is a mixed model.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] If the data from an experiment are analyzed with only one error term used in the model, misleading and invalid conclusions can be drawn from the results.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Similar to a split-plot design, a **strip-plot design** can result when some type of restricted randomization has occurred during the experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] A simple factorial design can result in a strip-plot design depending on how the experiment was conducted.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] As in the split-plot design, strip-plot designs result when the randomization in the experiment has been restricted in some way.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] As a result of the restricted randomization that occurs in strip-plot designs, there are multiple sizes of experimental units.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Therefore, there are different error terms or different error variances that are used to test the factors of interest in the design.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] A traditional strip-plot design has three sizes of experimental units.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Consider the following example from the semiconductor industry.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] An experiment requires an implant step and an anneal step.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] At both the anneal and the implant steps there are three factors to test.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The implant process accommodates 12 wafers in a batch, and implanting a single wafer under a specified set of conditions is not practical nor does doing so represent economical use of the implanter.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The anneal furnace can handle up to 100 wafers.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The settings for a two-level factorial design for the three factors in the implant step are denoted (A, B, C), and a two-level factorial design for the three factors in the anneal step are denoted (D, E, F).
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Also present are interaction effects between the implant factors and the anneal factors.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Therefore, this experiment contains three sizes of experimental units, each of which has a unique error term for estimating the significance of effects.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] To put actual physical meaning to each of the experimental units in the above example, consider each combination of implant and anneal steps as an individual wafer.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] A batch of eight wafers goes through the implant step first.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Treatment combination 3 in factors A, B, and C is the first implant treatment run.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] This implant treatment is applied to all eight wafers at once.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Once the first implant treatment is finished, another set of eight wafers is implanted with treatment combination 5 of factors A, B, and C.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] This continues until the last batch of eight wafers is implanted with treatment combination 6 of factors A, B, and C.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Once all of the eight treatment combinations of the implant factors have been run, the anneal step starts.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The first anneal treatment combination to be run is treatment combination 5 of factors D, E, and F.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] This anneal treatment combination is applied to a set of eight wafers, with each of these eight wafers coming from one of the eight implant treatment combinations.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] After this first batch of wafers has been annealed, the second anneal treatment is applied to a second batch of eight wafers, with these eight wafers coming from one each of the eight implant treatment combinations.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] This is continued until the last batch of eight wafers has been implanted with a particular combination of factors D, E, and F.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Running the experiment in this way results in a strip-plot design with three sizes of experimental units.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] A set of eight wafers that are implanted together is the experimental unit for the implant factors A, B, and C and for all of their interactions.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] There are eight experimental units for the implant factors.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] A different set of eight wafers are annealed together.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] This different set of eight wafers is the second size experimental unit and is the experimental unit for the anneal factors D, E, and F and for all of their interactions.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] The third size experimental unit is a single wafer.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] This is the experimental unit for all of the interaction effects between the implant factors and the anneal factors.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Actually, the above description of the strip-plot design represents one block or one replicate of this experiment.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] If the experiment contains no replication and the model for the implant contains only the main effects and two-factor interactions, the three-factor interaction term A*B*C (1 degree of freedom) provides the error term for the estimation of effects within the implant experimental unit.
[src:box-violin-plots/strip-plot] Invoking a similar model for the anneal experimental unit produces the three-factor interaction term D*E*F for the error term (1 degree of freedom) for effects within the anneal experimental unit.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] A **violin plot** (also known as a **bean plot**) is a statistical graphic for comparing probability distributions.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] It is similar to a box plot, but has enhanced information with the addition of a rotated kernel density plot on each side.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] The violin plot was proposed in 1997 by Jerry L.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] Nelson as a way to display even more information than box plots, which were created by John Tukey in 1977.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] The name comes from the plot's alleged resemblance to a violin.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] Violin plots are similar to box plots, except that they also show the probability density of the data at different values, usually smoothed by a kernel density estimator.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] A violin plot will include all the data that is in a box plot: a marker for the median of the data; a box or marker indicating the interquartile range; and possibly all sample points, if the number of samples is not too high.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] While a box plot shows a summary statistics such as median and interquartile ranges, the violin plot shows the full distribution of the data.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] The violin plot can be used in multimodal data (more than one peak).
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] In this case a violin plot shows the presence of different peaks, their position and relative amplitude.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] Like box plots, violin plots are used to represent comparison of a variable distribution (or sample distribution) across different "categories" (for example, temperature distribution compared between day and night, or distribution of car prices compared across different car makers).
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] For instance, the outer shape represents all possible results.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] The next layer inside might represent the values that occur 95% of the time.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] The next layer (if it exists) inside might represent the values that occur 50% of the time.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] Violin plots are less popular than box plots.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] Violin plots may be harder to understand for readers not familiar with them.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] In this case, a more accessible alternative is to plot a series of stacked histograms or kernel density plots.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] The original meaning of "violin plot" was a combination of a box plot and a two-sided kernel density plot.
[src:box-violin-plots/violin-plot] However, currently "violin plots" are sometimes understood just as two-sided kernel density plots, without a box plot or any other elements.
